Add a Component Story to Storybook

Our project’s StoryBook configuration tells it to look for files that have .stories in the name along with a JavaScript or TypeScript related component extension.

// inside .storybook/main.js

module.exports = {
  "stories": [
    "../**/*.stories.@(js|jsx|ts|tsx)"
  ],
	...
// inside .storybook/main.js

module.exports = {
  "stories": [
    "../**/*.stories.@(js|jsx|ts|tsx)"
  ],
	...

The stories included in the CampSpots application are all located in the exercise0-storybook directory.

How you choose to organize your project is up to you, but I prefer having them grouped together.

The Structure of a Component Story

The components that Storybook displays in the sidebar are configured by writing a Storybook Story in a format called the Component Story Format (CSF).

Let’s look at the story for the date picker component, located at DatePicker.stories.jsx inside of the exercise0-storybook directory.

At the top of the date picker story, we import React as well as the DatePicker component from components/date-picker/date-picker.

import React from 'react'
import DatePicker from 'components/date-picker/date-picker'
import React from 'react'
import DatePicker from 'components/date-picker/date-picker'

Every story that we write in the Component Story Format requires a configuration object that will be the default export for the file.

The title corresponds to what will be displayed in the Storybook sidebar. The component entry references the component it will render:

export default {
  title: 'Components/DatePicker',
  component: DatePicker,
}
export default {
  title: 'Components/DatePicker',
  component: DatePicker,
}

At the bottom of our Storybook Story file, we can create named exports that will render the component with specific props or other customizations. We'll look at that more later.

For now, we'll create an export called Default that will tell Storybook to render the <DatePicker/> component:

export const Default = () => <MegaNav/>;
export const Default = () => <MegaNav/>;

Supplying Options to a Storybook Story

The ListingExcerpt Component is used on the CampSpots Listings page to show information about the various sites available for reservations. But in Storybook, the component was displaying information about Disneyland.

Let’s look at how this is configured.

Back in your editor, open up ListingExcerpt.stories.jsx.

This story’s primary structure is similar to what we saw in the date picker story.

The difference here is the creation of a Template that maps args to the component.

In order to create a variation of the story, the Template is bound to an empty object. Then a structured args object that corresponds to the component’s props is applied to it.

Here’s how this process looks for creating the Default variation of the ListingExcerpt story:

// inside ListingExcerpt.stories.jsx

// We create a “template” of how args map to rendering
const Template = (args) => <ListingExcerpt {...args} />;

// Each story then reuses that template
export const Default = Template.bind({});

Default.args = {
  data: {
    listingName: "Disneyland",
    location: "Planet Earth",
    listingType: "Amusement Park",
    excerpt: "The happiest place on Earth",
    amenities: ["wifi", "food", "bathrooms"]
  },
  image: image
};
// inside ListingExcerpt.stories.jsx

// We create a “template” of how args map to rendering
const Template = (args) => <ListingExcerpt {...args} />;

// Each story then reuses that template
export const Default = Template.bind({});

Default.args = {
  data: {
    listingName: "Disneyland",
    location: "Planet Earth",
    listingType: "Amusement Park",
    excerpt: "The happiest place on Earth",
    amenities: ["wifi", "food", "bathrooms"]
  },
  image: image
};

We know what the shape of the args object should look like by looking at the expected props for the component we’re creating the story for.

The ListingExcerpt component at components/listing-excerpt.js has propTypes defined at the bottom of the file:

ListingExcerpt.propTypes = {
    id: PropTypes.string,
    data: PropTypes.shape({
        listingName: PropTypes.string,
        location: PropTypes.string,
        listingType: PropTypes.string,
        imageSrc: PropTypes.string,
        excerpt: PropTypes.string,
        amenities: PropTypes.array
    }),
    image: PropTypes.string
}
ListingExcerpt.propTypes = {
    id: PropTypes.string,
    data: PropTypes.shape({
        listingName: PropTypes.string,
        location: PropTypes.string,
        listingType: PropTypes.string,
        imageSrc: PropTypes.string,
        excerpt: PropTypes.string,
        amenities: PropTypes.array
    }),
    image: PropTypes.string
}

🛠 Challenge: Add a Story to Storybook

Now that we’ve looked at some examples of how Storybook Stories work, it’s your turn to create one.

On the Listings page there’s a custom Dropdown List component that allows the user to select what kind of sites they want to see.

Each of the individual items in the Dropdown List has a link, which is why it is a custom component instead of a select that would have to have a submit button.

The source code for the Dropdown Listing component can be found at components/dropdown-list.js.

Using the existing Storybook Story examples, create a new story for the Dropdown List component.

If you want to peek at the answer, a completed story can be found in the exercise0-storybook/answer directory.

🛠 Solution: Adding a Dropdown List Story to Storybook

First, create a new DropdownList.stories.jsx file.

Copying and pasting the base structure of a story and doing some renaming is a good way to speed things up:

import React from 'react';

import DropdownList from 'components/dropdown-list';

export default {
  title: 'Components/DropdownList',
  component: DropdownList,
}
import React from 'react';

import DropdownList from 'components/dropdown-list';

export default {
  title: 'Components/DropdownList',
  component: DropdownList,
}

Checking the component’s source code, we can see that there is a set of props that the Dropdown List expects:

// inside components/dropdown-list.js

DropdownList.propTypes = {
    defaultItemText: PropTypes.string,
    items: PropTypes.array
}
// inside components/dropdown-list.js

DropdownList.propTypes = {
    defaultItemText: PropTypes.string,
    items: PropTypes.array
}

Since we have some props that we need to pass, in our story we’ll follow the pattern of creating a Template and binding an empty object:

// We create a “template” of how args map to rendering
const Template = (args) => <DropdownList {...args} />;

// Each story then reuses that template
export const Default = Template.bind({});
// We create a “template” of how args map to rendering
const Template = (args) => <DropdownList {...args} />;

// Each story then reuses that template
export const Default = Template.bind({});

Finally, we’ll set up some args for the Default configuration of the story that match the structure of the props the component expects:

Default.args = {
  defaultItemText: 'Fruits',
  items: ['apples', 'pears', 'plums']
}; 
Default.args = {
  defaultItemText: 'Fruits',
  items: ['apples', 'pears', 'plums']
};

Refreshing Storybook, we can see that the new DropdownList component story is now available!

Checking DropdownList Accessibility

The Accessibility pane in Storybook shows that our DropdownList doesn’t have any issues.

However, we can’t use the keyboard to operate it!

Looking at the source in dropdown-list.js, we can see that the markdown was written with a div:

// inside dropdown-list.js

<div
	className="dropdown-btn"
	onClick={()=>{ setActive(!active) }}
>
	{defaultItemText}
</div>
// inside dropdown-list.js

<div
	className="dropdown-btn"
	onClick={()=>{ setActive(!active) }}
>
	{defaultItemText}
</div>

Replacing the div with the semantic button element will enable the DropdownList to be focusable and operable with the keyboard.

We can also see that a new “pass” has shown up in the Accessibility pane because that toggles the DropdownList has text.

Clicking the “More info” link below an issue in the Accessibility pane will take you to the axe-core docs where you can learn more about why the issue is important and how to go about fixing it.

Storybook’s Accessibility pane is great for catching issues that may have slipped by you or a teammate in the development process. Just remember, you should still test with a keyboard and screen reader, even if the tool doesn’t report any issues.
